{"title_page": "Jack Douglass", "text_new": "{{Other people||Jack Douglas (disambiguation){{!}}Jack Douglas}}\n{{Infobox YouTube personality\n| name            = Jack Douglass\n| image           = JacksfilmsMay2019.jpg\n| caption         = Douglass on ''Cold Ones'' on May 6, 2019\n| birth_name      = John Patrick Douglass\n| birth_date      = {{birth date and age|1988|6|30}}\n| birth_place     = [[Columbia, Maryland]], U.S.\n| nationality     = American\n| occupation      = [[List of YouTubers|YouTube personality]], comedian, musician\n|spouse          = {{marriage|Erin Breslin|2018}}\n| years_active    = 2006\u2013present\n| genre           = [[Satire]], music, comedy, memes\n| channel_name    = jacksfilms\n| channel_name2   = jackisanerd\n| channel_name3   = SHUTUPDENNIS\n|subscribers     = {{flatlist|\n* 4.72 million (jacksfilms) \n* 549 thousand (jackisanerd)\n* 39.6 thousand (SHUTUPDENNIS)\n}}\n| views           = {{flatlist|\n* 2.22 billion (jacksfilms)      \n* 55.8 million (jackisanerd)\n* 5.9 million (SHUTUPDENNIS)\n}}\n| network         = [[Fullscreen (company)|Fullscreen]]\n|associated_acts  = {{hlist|[[Toby Turner]]|[[Sean Klitzner]]|[[Olga Kay]]|[[Shane Dawson]]|[[PewDiePie]]|[[Fine Brothers]]|[[Michael Stevens (educator)|Michael Stevens]]|[[Vsauce#Vsauce2|Kevin Lieber]]|[[Vsauce#Vsauce3|Jake Roper]]|[[Markiplier]]|[[Ninja Sex Party]]|Charles Trippy|[[Grace Helbig]]|[[Michael Buckley (Internet celebrity)|Michael Buckley]]|[[Jacksepticeye]]|[[Flula Borg]]|[[Steve Zaragoza]]|[[Ryan Higa]]|[[Joey Graceffa]]|[[Jenna Marbles]]|[[JonTron]]|[[HowToBasic]]|[[Lilly Singh]]|[[Tay Zonday]]|[[Maddox (writer)|Maddox]]|[[Peter Hollens]]|[[Matthew Santoro]]|[[TomSka]]|[[Greg Benson]]|[[Craig Benzine]]|[[Harley Morenstein]]|[[Boogie2988]]|[[Portal A Interactive]]|[[iDubbbz]]|[[h3h3Productions]]|Erik Hoffstad|[[Rhett and Link]]|[[Cory Williams]]|[[Gus Johnson (comedian)|Gus Johnson]] [[Jenna Marbles]]}}\n| silver_year=2010 (jacksfilms),<br>2013  (jackisanerd)\n| gold_year=2013 (jacksfilms)\n| stats_update    = January 11, 2020\n| silver_button   = yes | gold_button     = yes}}\n'''John Patrick Douglass''' (born June 30, 1988), better known online as '''jacksfilms''' and '''Jack Douglass''' is an American [[YouTuber]], comedian, web-based entertainer, filmmaker and musician. \n\nHe began his career online in 2006, when he created his YouTube channel. His channel initially consisted of [[infomercial]] parodies, sketches, and comedic music videos. As his audience grew, he expanded into comedy series centered around viewer comments and submissions, such as ''Your Grammar Sucks'' (''YGS ''), ''JackAsk'', and ''Yesterday I Asked You'' (''YIAY'').\n\n== Early life and education ==\nDouglass was born in [[Columbia, Maryland|Columbia]], [[Maryland]] on June 30, 1988, and is primarily of [[Irish people|Irish]] ancestry.<ref>{{cite AV media|last=Douglass|first=Jack|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YcwGLjl2W_s|title=The CLICKBAIT Game (YIAY #304)|work=jacksfilms|publisher=[[YouTube]]|date=January 13, 2017|accessdate = January 13, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite AV media|last=Douglass|first=Jack||url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NZMIc3w-Llc|title=My Apology|work=jacksfilms|publisher=[[YouTube]]|date=May 1, 2017|accessdate=July 19, 2017}}</ref> He has two older sisters. Douglass went to elementary school and middle school in Maryland. During high school, he started to develop a love for music. He then began to play the [[French horn]] as well as the [[piano]]. \n\nIn May 2006, during his senior year of high school, he was given the task of making a video about all the books he had read during the year. He and his friends decided to film a series of short videos that made fun of books such as ''Beowulf'' and ''All the King's Men''. After making these sketches, he decided that he wanted to make films to a greater extent. By the next month, he had begun using YouTube and had started to upload videos.<ref>{{cite AV media|last=Douglass|first=Jack|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SAHDywxvxuw|title=DRAW MY LIFE - Jack Douglass|work=jacksfilms|publisher=[[YouTube]]|date=July 19, 2013|accessdate=December 10, 2015}}</ref>\n \nAfter graduating from [[Atholton High School]], Douglass went to [[American University]], where he majored in film and minored in music theory.<ref name=WashTimes2009>{{cite web|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2009/nov/11/cashing-in-big-on-viral-videos/|title=Cashing in big on viral videos|work=[[The Washington Times]]|date=November 11, 2009|accessdate=May 31, 2012}}</ref>\n\n== YouTube career ==\n===jacksfilms channel===\n==== Early years and ''Your Grammar Sucks'' (2006\u20132013) ====\nDouglass launched his main YouTube channel, jacksfilms, on June 26, 2006.<ref name=YTabout>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/user/jacksfilms/about|title=jacksfilms \u2013 YouTube about page|publisher=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=April 2, 2020}}</ref> His first video was a commercial for a fictional device, the Handy Pen, and featured himself and his family members. Later, he uploaded ''The WTF Blanket ([[Snuggie]] Parody)'' on January 22, 2009.<ref name=WashTimes2009/><ref name=Popken2009>{{cite web|last=Popken|first=Ben|url=http://consumerist.com/2009/01/you-say-snuggie-i-say-wtf-blanket.html|title=You Say Snuggie, I Say WTF Blanket|work=[[Consumerist|The Consumerist]]|date=January 31, 2009|accessdate=June 29, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.collegehumor.com/video/3863361/the-wtf-blanket |title=The WTF Blanket |publisher=[[CollegeHumor]] |date=January 26, 2009 |accessdate=May 24, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607220439/http://www.collegehumor.com/video/3863361/the-wtf-blanket |archive-date=June 7, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=Nudd2009>{{cite web|last=Nudd|first=Tim|url=http://www.adweek.com/adfreak/be-utter-tool-order-wtf-blanket-now-14652|title=Be an utter tool, order the WTF Blanket now|work=[[Adweek]]|date=February 12, 2009|accessdate=May 24, 2012}}</ref> which has become his most popular video.<ref name=May2009>{{cite web|last=May|first=Brookes|url=http://www.theeagleonline.com/news/story/student-strikes-youtube-gold/|title=Student strikes YouTube gold|work=The Eagle|date=October 25, 2009|accessdate=May 24, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121108110454/http://www.theeagleonline.com/news/story/student-strikes-youtube-gold/|archive-date=November 8, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> Many of Douglass' early videos were parodies, often about [[infomercials]] and [[Apple Inc.|Apple]] products.<ref name=Kaiser2012>{{cite web|last=Kaiser|first=Lukas|url=http://humor.about.com/od/viralvideos/tp/jacks_films.htm|title=The Commercial Parodies of Jacks Films|website=[[Dotdash|About.com]]|date=2010|accessdate=May 24, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120117171015/http://humor.about.com/od/viralvideos/tp/jacks_films.htm|archive-date=January 17, 2012|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=Miragliotta2011>{{cite web|last=Miragliotta|first=Joe|url=http://www.joesdaily.com/2011/10/05/the-new-iphone-4s-parody-by-jacksfilms/|title=THE NEW IPHONE 4S (PARODY) BY JACKSFILMS|work=Joe's Daily|date=October 5, 2011|accessdate=May 24, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://apple.mmgn.com/Videos/The-Magical-iPad-parody |title=The Magical iPad(parody)|work=MMGN|date=September 13, 2010|accessdate=May 24, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100918031622/http://apple.mmgn.com/Videos/The-Magical-iPad-parody |archive-date=September 18, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Douglass's earliest content also included various parodies about smartphones from Apple and Samsung, first starting with a parody of the [[iPhone 4S]].\n\nIn June 2011, Douglass visited [[Electronic Entertainment Expo 2011]] (E3 2011) to help Toby Turner film footage for a video. In 2012, Douglass attended [[E3 2012|E3]], this time to promote [[GREE]]. Later that month, during [[VidCon#2012 (3rd annual VidCon)|VidCon 2012]], Douglass performed a live edition of his ''Your Grammar Sucks'' series. Douglass, alongside Toby Turner and Sean Klitzner, performed a live version of their ''Sideburns'' Song at [[VidCon|VidCon 2012]] as well.<ref>{{Citation|url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bTA5CNI8yYo|accessdate = December 16, 2015|title = VidCon 2012 \"Sideburns\" Live Performance}}</ref> \n\n[[File:JacksFilms (7486844900) (cropped).jpg|thumb|right|upright|Douglass at [[VidCon 2012]]]]\nOn July 1, 2012, jacksfilms reached a total of 100 million video views on his channel. On December 16 the same year, the [[Fine Brothers]] released a video titled \"Teens React to Jacksfilms\".<ref>{{cite AV media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=A39cuQDl1GI|title=TEENS REACT TO JACKSFILMS|work=[[Fine Brothers Entertainment|FBE]]|publisher=[[YouTube]]|date=December 16, 2012|accessdate=December 11, 2013}}</ref> Douglass saw a rapid rise in subscribers, gaining almost 100,000 in the following week. On June 27, 2013, the jacksfilms channel reached 1 million subscribers.<ref name=Gutelle2013>{{cite web|last=Gutelle|first=Sam|url=http://www.tubefilter.com/2013/07/18/jacksfilms-jack-douglass-youtube-millionaires-your-grammar-sucks/|title=YouTube Millionaires: Jacksfilms Now Has Over One Million 'Biches'.|work=[[Tubefilter]]|date=July 18, 2013|accessdate=August 25, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet|user=jacksfilms|number=350305281709834240|date=June 27, 2013|title=1 MILLION SUBSCRIBERS!!!|accessdate=August 25, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Douglass' channel jacksfilms was listed on ''[[NewMediaRockstars]]''{{'}} list of the top 100 YouTube channels, ranked at #54.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://newmediarockstars.com/2014/12/the-nmr-top-100-youtube-channels-75-51/|title=The NMR Top 100 YouTube Channels: 75-51!|work=[[NewMediaRockstars]]|date=December 30, 2014|accessdate=January 6, 2015}}</ref> On November 20, 2015, the same day as \"Your Grammar Sucks 100\" released, Douglass hit 2 million subscribers.{{Citation needed|date=November 2015}}\n\nDouglass appeared in the 2016 and 2017 editions of ''[[YouTube Rewind]]''.<ref>{{cite AV media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FlsCjmMhFmw|title=YouTube Rewind: The Shape of 2017 {{!}} #YouTubeRewind|date=December 6, 2017|accessdate=December 8, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"rewind\" /> On June 29, 2017, Douglass celebrated his 11th anniversary on YouTube with a 16-minute compilation of his parodies, music videos and sketches.<ref>{{cite web|last=Douglass|first=Jack|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=j1h6XsIIQvc|title=11 Years on YouTube.|work=jacksfilms|publisher=[[YouTube]]||date=June 29, 2017|accessdate=October 3, 2017}}</ref> On July 27, 2017, the day before the release of his ''Emoji Movie'' review video, he hit 3 million subscribers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://socialblade.com/youtube/user/jacksfilms/monthly|title=jacksfilms Monthly YouTube Statistics - Socialblade.com|publisher=[[Social Blade]]|accessdate=December 8, 2017}}</ref> On April 1, 2018, he hit 4 million subscribers. On April 15, 2018, Douglass won the 2018 [[Shorty Awards|Shorty Award]] for YouTuber of the Year, which he accepted while dressed in a [[Garfield]] costume.<ref name=Shorty2018>{{cite web|url=http://shortyawards.com/category/10th/youtuber|title=YouTuber of the Year|publisher=[[Shorty Awards]]|accessdate=April 16, 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180416064848/http://shortyawards.com/category/10th/youtuber|archivedate=April 16, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==== ''JackAsk'' and ''Yesterday I Asked You'' (2014\u2013present) ====\n<!-- linked from redirects [[YIAY]] and [[Yiay]] -->\nOn January 8, 2014, Douglass launched a new series entitled ''JackAsk'', in which he answers viewers' questions in a satirical way. The intro and logo for the series are a reference to the TV series of a similar name, [[Jackass (TV series)|Jackass]]. {{As of|2020|03|df=}}, there are 100 episodes.\n\nOn February 3, 2015, Douglass started a daily series on his secondary channel jackisanerd, titled ''Yesterday I Asked You'' (''YIAY''), in which he asks his viewers a question and reads his favorite answers to the viewers. After 15 days of uploading ''YIAY'' videos to his second channel, jackisanerd, he moved the series to his main channel, jacksfilms, and has released episodes on it since. As of March 2020, he has uploaded 499 episodes making it the biggest series on his channel. He also briefly operated a live version of this series known as ''YIAY LIVE'' in which he had live viewers compete for the best answer to a given question.\n\nOn November 20, 2015, Douglass started a new series on the [[Regal Cinemas]] YouTube channel named ''Jack Talks Trailers'', in which he gives a brief recap of new film trailers that are released within the past week. At the end of each episode, Douglass reads the opinions of people's thoughts about a specific trailer shown in the episode. Douglass' last video for Regal was uploaded July 29, 2016.<ref>{{Citation|last=Regal Cinemas|title=Jack Talks Trailers: Episode 1: Finding Dory & Warcraft - Regal Cinemas [HD]|date=November 20, 2015|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cdpR40Hh63o|accessdate=May 13, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=jacksfilms|title=NEW SERIES!|date=November 21, 2015|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JIbZFjYTCbE|accessdate=May 13, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn March 21, 2016, Douglass uploaded an [[iPhone SE (1st generation)|first-generation iPhone SE]] parody in which he mocks the phone for the small screen size.<ref>{{cite web|title=iPhone SE parody commercial says what everyone's thinking|url=https://www.cnet.com/au/news/iphone-se-parody-commercial-says-what-everyones-thinking/|website=CNET|accessdate=17 September 2017|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Douglass|first1=Jack|title=iPhone SE (parody)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Bfktt22nUG4|website=YouTube|date=21 March 2016}}</ref> In March 2017, Douglass uploaded a video titled ''[[Samsung Galaxy S8|Galaxy S8]] first look (parody)'' which has earned more than a million views.<ref name=\"cnetS8\">{{cite web|title=Samsung Galaxy S8 video trending on YouTube isn't flattering|url=https://www.cnet.com/au/news/samsung-galaxy-s8-video-trending-on-youtube-isnt-flattering/|website=CNET|accessdate=17 September 2017|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Douglass|first1=Jack|title=Galaxy S8 first look (parody)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2WMEPWEavRY|website=YouTube|accessdate=17 September 2017|date=29 March 2017}}</ref> In September, Douglass made an [[iPhone X]] parody which has over 3 million views (making joking claims including, \"The [[Face ID]] shoot[s] thousands of lasers straight into your pores. Then it sucks out your soul, much like a [[Dementor]]\").<ref>{{cite web|title=It's What Steve Jobs Would've Wanted|url=https://www.kotaku.com.au/2017/09/its-what-steve-jobs-wouldve-wanted/|website=Kotaku Australia|accessdate=17 September 2017|language=en|date=14 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Douglass|first1=Jack|title=iPhone X (parody)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sjlHnJvXdQs|website=YouTube|accessdate=17 September 2017|date=12 September 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"cnetX\">{{cite web|title=Apple iPhone X parody video snarks at '$1,000 emoji machine'|url=https://www.cnet.com/au/news/apple-iphone-x-parody-jacksfilms-emoji-machine-video/|website=CNET|accessdate=17 September 2017|language=en}}</ref> Douglass also made several references to ''[[Game of Thrones]]'' in the videos.<ref name=\"cnetS8\" /><ref name=\"cnetX\" />\n\nDouglass appeared in [[YouTube Rewind#.22YouTube Rewind: The Ultimate 2016 Challenge.22|YouTube Rewind 2016]] and [[YouTube Rewind#.22YouTube Rewind: The Ultimate 2016 Challenge.22|YouTube Rewind 2017]].<ref name=\"rewind\">{{cite web|last1=Douglass|first1=Jake|title=TOO HOT for YOUTUBE REWIND? (JackAsk #74)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=e7KLLikFHys|website=YouTube|accessdate=17 September 2017|date=14 December 2016}}</ref> He also attended [[E3 2017]], where he filmed a sketch video; and [[E3 2018]], where he filmed an episode of YIAY.\n\nOn January 30, 2017, Douglass referred to ''[[The Emoji Movie]]'' for the first time in his video ''How do we fix YouTube? (YIAY #309)''.<ref>{{cite web|author1=jacksfilms|title=How do we fix YouTube? (YIAY #309)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5vTYaAU0nrw|website=YouTube|accessdate=1 August 2017|date=30 January 2017}}</ref> Douglass referenced ''The Emoji Movie'' frequently in 2017, making a parody of the trailer and selling merchandise of the date of its release, July 28. His videos, \"''Frame-by-frame analysis of The Emoji Movie Trailer''\", \"''THE EMOJI MOVIE - Trailer #2''\", and \"''Counting down to The Emoji Movie while spinning 15 [[fidget spinner]]s and [[Dab (dance)|dabbing]] every 60 seconds''\" have over 5 million views combined, {{as of|2017|11|lc=y}}.<ref>{{cite web|title=THE EMOJI MOVIE - Trailer #2|url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=e1C6bm52f5Q|publisher=YouTube|work=jacksfilms|date=April 27, 2017|accessdate = July 15, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=JULY 28 - UNISEX T-SHIRT|url=https://shop.crowdmade.com/collections/jacksfilms/products/emoji-movie-2-unisex-t-shirt|publisher=Crowdmade|work=jacksfilms|date=April 27, 2017|accessdate=July 15, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170728200743/https://shop.crowdmade.com/collections/jacksfilms/products/emoji-movie-2-unisex-t-shirt|archive-date=July 28, 2017|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On July 20, Douglass received a package from the marketing team at [[Sony Pictures Animation]], thanking him for being \"the [No. 1] fan of ''The Emoji Movie''\", inviting him to the world premiere on July 23, and sending ''Emoji Movie''-related merchandise, including fidget spinners, face masks of ''Emoji Movie'' characters, and a [[Stuffed toy|plushie]] of Poop.<ref>{{cite web |last=Dryden |first=Liam |url=http://www.wetheunicorns.com/news/jacksfilms-emoji-movie-premiere/ |title=JacksFilms Got The Best Response After Trolling The Sh*t Out Of 'The Emoji Movie' |date=July 21, 2017 |work=We the Unicorns |accessdate=July 22, 2017}}</ref> The video in which Douglass unboxed the package and discussed his invitation has received over 2 million views.<ref>{{cite web|title=I got invited to the world premiere of The Emoji Movie|url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=D1-Lnk99G1U|publisher=YouTube|work=jacksfilms|date=July 21, 2017|accessdate = July 15, 2017}}</ref> On July 28, Douglass uploaded a review of the film, hinting at the large amounts of product placement but generally acting as if he enjoyed the film. The review has received over 6 million views.<ref>{{cite web|author1=jacksfilms|title=THE EMOJI MOVIE REVIEW|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UWn8zsYtbtY|website=YouTube|accessdate=28 July 2017|date=28 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2019, Douglass posted a video where he asked people on the street, \"Can ANYONE name a single character from the movie ''[[Avatar (2009 film)|Avatar]]''?\". Only one respondent was able to name a character from the film.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Neilan |first1=Dan |title=Nobody can name a single character in Avatar, apparently |url=https://news.avclub.com/nobody-can-name-a-single-character-in-avatar-apparentl-1833493985 |website=The A.V. Club |accessdate=March 26, 2019 |date=March 22, 2019}}</ref> In May, Douglass posted a video titled \"Watch Endgame. Beat Avatar.\", in which he urged the viewers to watch ''[[Avengers: Endgame]]'' and make the film take ''Avatar's'' title as \"[[List of highest-grossing films|The top-grossing film of all time]]\".<ref>{{cite web|author1=jacksfilms|title=Watch Endgame. Beat Avatar.|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Eb9Z8gutG8I|website=YouTube|date=May 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Collaborations and other appearances ===\n<!-- linked from redirect [[The Sideburns Crew]] -->\n[[File:TobyTurnerJackDouglassVidCon2012.jpg|thumb|Douglass performing with [[Toby Turner]] at [[VidCon 2012]]]]\nDouglass' relocation to [[Los Angeles]] from [[Maryland]] offered opportunities to collaborate with fellow YouTube users and expand his audience. The success of his collaborations with [[Toby Turner]] and [[Sean Klitzner]] led to the trio being nicknamed \"The Sideburns Crew\".<ref name=\"YGS100video\">{{cite AV media|url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AEmPk7uAQ34|title=YGS #100|publisher=[[YouTube]]|work=jacksfilms|date=November 20, 2015|accessdate = December 10, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Douglass|first1=Jack|title=THE VALENTINES DAY SONG|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DXtXHkgalwM|website=YouTube|accessdate=17 September 2017|date=14 February 2012}}</ref> Douglass also filmed videos for Los Angeles-based YouTube partner Olga Karavaeva, more commonly referred to as [[Olga Kay]]. He has also collaborated with [[Shane Dawson]], Vincent Cyr, [[Onision]] and Stefan Li among others. Douglass has also featured as a voice guest in the asdfmovie series and other sketches by [[TomSka]]. On September 26, 2011, Douglass uploaded \"Take Off Your Clothes (Like [[Scarlett Johansson]])\".<ref>{{cite web|author=Joe Miragliotta|url=http://www.joesdaily.com/2011/09/26/take-off-your-clothes-like-scarlett-johansson/|title=TAKE OFF YOUR CLOTHES (LIKE SCARLETT JOHANSSON)|publisher=Joe's Daily|date=September 26, 2011|accessdate=June 29, 2012}}</ref> On July 23, 2012, he uploaded \"The Ray William Johnson Song\", which featured ten other YouTube stars including Olga Kay, [[PewDiePie|Felix Kjellberg]] and [[Steve Kardynal]]. On September 23, 2012, he uploaded \"''Your Grammar Sucks #40''\", which featured YouTube performers including the [[Fine Brothers]] and Brock Baker. Douglass has appeared on the [[h3h3Productions|H3 Podcast]] numerous times, typically accompanied by fellow YouTube creator Erik Hoffstad. A September 2017 episode featuring Douglass gained notable controversy after host Ethan Klein's criticism of [[PewDiePie]]'s use of the [[Nigger|\"N-word\"]] during a livestream, receiving over 30 thousand dislikes.<ref>{{Citation|url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=W555pdLeI_I|accessdate = February 22, 2019|title = H3 Podcast #17}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ey7zaPv00fo|accessdate = February 22, 2019|title = H3 Podcast #29}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3wV4TxJ8dA8|accessdate = February 22, 2019|title = H3 Podcast #46}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OcQl2ra57ME|accessdate = February 22, 2019|title = H3 Podcast #64}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0oLt5qfxtxQ|accessdate = February 22, 2019|title = H3 Podcast #98}}</ref>\n\nDouglass is also known for playing the role of [[List of MyMusic characters#Intern 2/Flowchart|Intern 2]] on ''[[MyMusic]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://whatstrending.com/2013/09/jack-douglass-adam-busch-mymusic-season-2-making-youtube-magic-fine-bros/|title=Jack Douglass And Adam Busch On \"MyMusic\" Season 2 And Making YouTube Magic with the Fine Bros|author=Amanda Walgrove|first=|date=September 6, 2013|website=|publisher=What's Trending?|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131004221240/http://whatstrending.com/2013/09/jack-douglass-adam-busch-mymusic-season-2-making-youtube-magic-fine-bros/|archivedate=October 4, 2013|accessdate=October 1, 2013}}</ref> a defunct show funded by YouTube's $100&nbsp;million [[YouTube Original Channel Initiative|original channel initiative]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.techi.com/2011/10/youtube-expands-its-exclusive-content-drive-with-100-new-video-channels/|title=YouTube expands its exclusive-content drive with 100 new video channels|author=Connor Livingston|first=|date=October 29, 2011|website=|publisher=Techi|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160322122712/http://www.techi.com/2011/10/youtube-expands-its-exclusive-content-drive-with-100-new-video-channels/|archive-date=March 22, 2016|accessdate=June 9, 2013}}</ref> ''[[MyMusic]]'' has over 430,000 subscribers and over 48.2&nbsp;million video views as of September 4, 2018.\n\nIn 2014, Douglass began voicing Jimmy, the protagonist in ''16-Bit High'', an animated series launched by [[Smosh Games]].<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Jarvey|first=Natalie|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/sxsw-smosh-games-launches-two-686776|title=SXSW Exclusive: Smosh Games Launches Two New YouTube Series (Video)|magazine=Hollywood Reporter|date=March 7, 2014|accessdate=April 7, 2014}}</ref> In October 2015, Douglass portrayed \"Pippen\" in the film ''[[Bob Thunder: Internet Assassin]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSnCCN4LPs3B+1d9+MKW20150925 |title=Influencer Comedy Film \"Bob Thunder: Internet Assassin\" Trailer Debuts |work=Reuters |date=September 25, 2015 |accessdate=April 16, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160426005555/https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSnCCN4LPs3B%2B1d9%2BMKW20150925 |archive-date=April 26, 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\n<!-- linked from redirect [[Kristen Klessig]] -->\n\nOn January 1, 2017, Douglass became engaged to his longtime partner Erin Elizabeth Breslin.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.j-14.com/posts/youtube-jack-douglass-engaged-erin-elizabeth-breslin-122557/photos/kelsea1-221818 |title=YouTube Star Jack Douglass Is Engaged to Longtime Girlfriend Erin Elizabeth Breslin |last=Rodriguez |first=Karla |website=[[J-14 (magazine)|J-14]] |publication-date=January 6, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Jacksfilms on Twitter|url=https://twitter.com/jacksfilms/status/816127315449118721|website=Twitter|accessdate=2 August 2017}}</ref> The couple married on April 21, 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BecHPxqHOHZ/|title=Instagram post by E.E. \ud83c\udf40 \u2022 Jan 27, 2018 at 4:20am UTC|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=2018-02-05}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=jacksfilms|title=Wedding Hashtags (YIAY #330)|date=2017-05-22|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3J43TouOsqM|accessdate=2017-12-08}}</ref> Douglass owns two [[American Eskimo Dog|American Eskimo]] dogs named Klondike and Sundae. Their dog, Klondike inspired Douglass to create a new line of merchandise named after her. A semi-satirical dig at [[Logan Paul]]'s \"Be a Maverick\" clothing line, the line features images of the Eskimo dog.\n\n== Awards ==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Nominated\n! Award\n! Result\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | {{abbr|Ref(s)|References}}\n|-\n| 2018\n| [[Shorty Awards]]\n| YouTuber of the Year\n| {{won}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |<ref name=Shorty2018/>\n|-\n| 2018\n| [[Streamy Awards]]\n| Overall Comedy\n| {{nominated}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.streamys.org/nominees-winners/8th-annual-nominees/|title=8th Annual Nominees|work=The Streamy Awards|access-date=2018-10-24|language=en-US}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCPcFg7aBbaVzXoIKSNqwaww jacksfilms YouTube channel]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/user/jackisanerd jackisanerd YouTube channel]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120717131845/http://www.vokle.com/series/24487-get-jackd Jack Douglass' ''GET JACK'D'' live chat series] on [[Vokle]] \n* [https://itunes.apple.com/us/artist/jack-douglass/id115996508 Douglass' music] on [[iTunes]]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Douglass, Jack}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American comedians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:American male comedians]]\n[[Category:American male musicians]]\n[[Category:American male voice actors]]\n[[Category:American male web series actors]]\n[[Category:American people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:American University alumni]]\n[[Category:American YouTubers]]\n[[Category:Atholton High School alumni]]\n[[Category:Comedy YouTubers]]\n[[Category:Fullscreen (company) people]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male YouTubers]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Maryland]]\n[[Category:People from Columbia, Maryland]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from Maryland]]\n[[Category:Infomercial parodies]]\n[[Category:Music YouTubers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other people||Jack Douglas (disambiguation){{!}}Jack Douglas}}\n{{Infobox YouTube personality\n| name            = Jack Douglass\n| image           = JacksfilmsMay2019.jpg\n| caption         = Douglass on ''Cold Ones'' on May 6, 2019\n| birth_name      = John Patrick Douglass\n| birth_date      = {{birth date and age|1988|6|30}}\n| birth_place     = [[Columbia, Maryland]], U.S.\n| nationality     = American\n| occupation      = [[List of YouTubers|YouTube personality]], comedian, musician\n|spouse          = {{marriage|Erin Breslin|2018}}\n| years_active    = 2006\u2013present\n| genre           = [[Satire]], music, comedy, memes\n| channel_name    = jacksfilms\n| channel_name2   = jackisanerd\n| channel_name3   = SHUTUPDENNIS\n|subscribers     = {{flatlist|\n* 4.72 million (jacksfilms) \n* 549 thousand (jackisanerd)\n* 39.6 thousand (SHUTUPDENNIS)\n}}\n| views           = {{flatlist|\n* 2.22 billion (jacksfilms)      \n* 55.8 million (jackisanerd)\n* 5.9 million (SHUTUPDENNIS)\n}}\n| network         = [[Fullscreen (company)|Fullscreen]]\n|associated_acts  = {{hlist|[[Toby Turner]]|[[Sean Klitzner]]|[[Olga Kay]]|[[Shane Dawson]]|[[PewDiePie]]|[[Fine Brothers]]|[[Michael Stevens (educator)|Michael Stevens]]|[[Vsauce#Vsauce2|Kevin Lieber]]|[[Vsauce#Vsauce3|Jake Roper]]|[[Markiplier]]|[[Ninja Sex Party]]|Charles Trippy|[[Grace Helbig]]|[[Michael Buckley (Internet celebrity)|Michael Buckley]]|[[Jacksepticeye]]|[[Flula Borg]]|[[Steve Zaragoza]]|[[Ryan Higa]]|[[Joey Graceffa]]|[[Jenna Marbles]]|[[JonTron]]|[[HowToBasic]]|[[Lilly Singh]]|[[Tay Zonday]]|[[Maddox (writer)|Maddox]]|[[Peter Hollens]]|[[Matthew Santoro]]|[[TomSka]]|[[Greg Benson]]|[[Craig Benzine]]|[[Harley Morenstein]]|[[Boogie2988]]|[[Portal A Interactive]]|[[iDubbbz]]|[[h3h3Productions]]|Erik Hoffstad|[[Rhett and Link]]|[[Cory Williams]]|[[Gus Johnson (comedian)|Gus Johnson]] [[Jenna Marbles]]}}\n| silver_year=2010 (jacksfilms),<br>2013  (jackisanerd)\n| gold_year=2013 (jacksfilms)\n| stats_update    = January 11, 2020\n| silver_button   = yes | gold_button     = yes}}\n'''John Patrick Douglass''' (born June 30, 1988), better known online as '''jacksfilms''' and '''Jack Douglass''' is an American [[YouTuber]], comedian, web-based entertainer, filmmaker and musician. He began his career online in 2006, when he created his YouTube channel. His channel initially consisted of [[infomercial]] parodies, sketches, and comedic music videos. As his audience grew, he expanded into comedy series centered around viewer comments and submissions, such as ''Your Grammar Sucks'' (''YGS ''), ''JackAsk'', and ''Yesterday I Asked You'' (''YIAY'').\n\n== Early life and education ==\nDouglass was born in [[Columbia, Maryland|Columbia]], [[Maryland]] on June 30, 1988, and is primarily of [[Irish people|Irish]] ancestry.<ref>{{cite AV media|last=Douglass|first=Jack|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YcwGLjl2W_s|title=The CLICKBAIT Game (YIAY #304)|work=jacksfilms|publisher=[[YouTube]]|date=January 13, 2017|accessdate = January 13, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite AV media|last=Douglass|first=Jack||url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NZMIc3w-Llc|title=My Apology|work=jacksfilms|publisher=[[YouTube]]|date=May 1, 2017|accessdate=July 19, 2017}}</ref> He has two older sisters. Douglass went to elementary school and middle school in Maryland. During high school, he started to develop a love for music. He then began to play the [[French horn]] as well as the [[piano]]. In May 2006, during his senior year of high school, he was given the task of making a video about all the books he had read during the year. He and his friends decided to film a series of short videos that made fun of books such as ''Beowulf'' and ''All the King's Men''. After making these sketches, he decided that he wanted to make films to a greater extent. By the next month, he had begun using YouTube and had started to upload videos.<ref>{{cite AV media|last=Douglass|first=Jack|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SAHDywxvxuw|title=DRAW MY LIFE - Jack Douglass|work=jacksfilms|publisher=[[YouTube]]|date=July 19, 2013|accessdate=December 10, 2015}}</ref>\n \nAfter graduating from [[Atholton High School]], Douglass went to [[American University]], where he majored in film and minored in music theory.<ref name=WashTimes2009>{{cite web|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2009/nov/11/cashing-in-big-on-viral-videos/|title=Cashing in big on viral videos|work=[[The Washington Times]]|date=November 11, 2009|accessdate=May 31, 2012}}</ref>\n\n== YouTube career ==\n===jacksfilms channel===\n==== Early years and ''Your Grammar Sucks'' (2006\u20132013) ====\nDouglass launched his main YouTube channel, jacksfilms, on June 26, 2006.<ref name=YTabout>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/user/jacksfilms/about|title=jacksfilms \u2013 YouTube about page|publisher=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=April 2, 2020}}</ref> His first video was a commercial for a fictional device, the Handy Pen, and featured himself and his family members. Later, he uploaded ''The WTF Blanket ([[Snuggie]] Parody)'' on January 22, 2009.<ref name=WashTimes2009/><ref name=Popken2009>{{cite web|last=Popken|first=Ben|url=http://consumerist.com/2009/01/you-say-snuggie-i-say-wtf-blanket.html|title=You Say Snuggie, I Say WTF Blanket|work=[[Consumerist|The Consumerist]]|date=January 31, 2009|accessdate=June 29, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.collegehumor.com/video/3863361/the-wtf-blanket |title=The WTF Blanket |publisher=[[CollegeHumor]] |date=January 26, 2009 |accessdate=May 24, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607220439/http://www.collegehumor.com/video/3863361/the-wtf-blanket |archive-date=June 7, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=Nudd2009>{{cite web|last=Nudd|first=Tim|url=http://www.adweek.com/adfreak/be-utter-tool-order-wtf-blanket-now-14652|title=Be an utter tool, order the WTF Blanket now|work=[[Adweek]]|date=February 12, 2009|accessdate=May 24, 2012}}</ref> which has become his most popular video.<ref name=May2009>{{cite web|last=May|first=Brookes|url=http://www.theeagleonline.com/news/story/student-strikes-youtube-gold/|title=Student strikes YouTube gold|work=The Eagle|date=October 25, 2009|accessdate=May 24, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121108110454/http://www.theeagleonline.com/news/story/student-strikes-youtube-gold/|archive-date=November 8, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> Many of Douglass' early videos were parodies, often about [[infomercials]] and [[Apple Inc.|Apple]] products.<ref name=Kaiser2012>{{cite web|last=Kaiser|first=Lukas|url=http://humor.about.com/od/viralvideos/tp/jacks_films.htm|title=The Commercial Parodies of Jacks Films|website=[[Dotdash|About.com]]|date=2010|accessdate=May 24, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120117171015/http://humor.about.com/od/viralvideos/tp/jacks_films.htm|archive-date=January 17, 2012|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=Miragliotta2011>{{cite web|last=Miragliotta|first=Joe|url=http://www.joesdaily.com/2011/10/05/the-new-iphone-4s-parody-by-jacksfilms/|title=THE NEW IPHONE 4S (PARODY) BY JACKSFILMS|work=Joe's Daily|date=October 5, 2011|accessdate=May 24, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://apple.mmgn.com/Videos/The-Magical-iPad-parody |title=The Magical iPad(parody)|work=MMGN|date=September 13, 2010|accessdate=May 24, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100918031622/http://apple.mmgn.com/Videos/The-Magical-iPad-parody |archive-date=September 18, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Douglass's earliest content also included various parodies about smartphones from Apple and Samsung, first starting with a parody of the [[iPhone 4S]].\n\nIn June 2011, Douglass visited [[Electronic Entertainment Expo 2011]] (E3 2011) to help Toby Turner film footage for a video. In 2012, Douglass attended [[E3 2012|E3]], this time to promote [[GREE]]. Later that month, during [[VidCon#2012 (3rd annual VidCon)|VidCon 2012]], Douglass performed a live edition of his ''Your Grammar Sucks'' series. Douglass, alongside Toby Turner and Sean Klitzner, performed a live version of their ''Sideburns'' Song at [[VidCon|VidCon 2012]] as well.<ref>{{Citation|url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bTA5CNI8yYo|accessdate = December 16, 2015|title = VidCon 2012 \"Sideburns\" Live Performance}}</ref> \n\n[[File:JacksFilms (7486844900) (cropped).jpg|thumb|right|upright|Douglass at [[VidCon 2012]]]]\nOn July 1, 2012, jacksfilms reached a total of 100 million video views on his channel. On December 16 the same year, the [[Fine Brothers]] released a video titled \"Teens React to Jacksfilms\".<ref>{{cite AV media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=A39cuQDl1GI|title=TEENS REACT TO JACKSFILMS|work=[[Fine Brothers Entertainment|FBE]]|publisher=[[YouTube]]|date=December 16, 2012|accessdate=December 11, 2013}}</ref> Douglass saw a rapid rise in subscribers, gaining almost 100,000 in the following week. On June 27, 2013, the jacksfilms channel reached 1 million subscribers.<ref name=Gutelle2013>{{cite web|last=Gutelle|first=Sam|url=http://www.tubefilter.com/2013/07/18/jacksfilms-jack-douglass-youtube-millionaires-your-grammar-sucks/|title=YouTube Millionaires: Jacksfilms Now Has Over One Million 'Biches'.|work=[[Tubefilter]]|date=July 18, 2013|accessdate=August 25, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet|user=jacksfilms|number=350305281709834240|date=June 27, 2013|title=1 MILLION SUBSCRIBERS!!!|accessdate=August 25, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Douglass' channel jacksfilms was listed on ''[[NewMediaRockstars]]''{{'}} list of the top 100 YouTube channels, ranked at #54.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://newmediarockstars.com/2014/12/the-nmr-top-100-youtube-channels-75-51/|title=The NMR Top 100 YouTube Channels: 75-51!|work=[[NewMediaRockstars]]|date=December 30, 2014|accessdate=January 6, 2015}}</ref> On November 20, 2015, the same day as \"Your Grammar Sucks 100\" released, Douglass hit 2 million subscribers.{{Citation needed|date=November 2015}}\n\nDouglass appeared in the 2016 and 2017 editions of ''[[YouTube Rewind]]''.<ref>{{cite AV media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FlsCjmMhFmw|title=YouTube Rewind: The Shape of 2017 {{!}} #YouTubeRewind|date=December 6, 2017|accessdate=December 8, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"rewind\" /> On June 29, 2017, Douglass celebrated his 11th anniversary on YouTube with a 16-minute compilation of his parodies, music videos and sketches.<ref>{{cite web|last=Douglass|first=Jack|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=j1h6XsIIQvc|title=11 Years on YouTube.|work=jacksfilms|publisher=[[YouTube]]||date=June 29, 2017|accessdate=October 3, 2017}}</ref> On July 27, 2017, the day before the release of his ''Emoji Movie'' review video, he hit 3 million subscribers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://socialblade.com/youtube/user/jacksfilms/monthly|title=jacksfilms Monthly YouTube Statistics - Socialblade.com|publisher=[[Social Blade]]|accessdate=December 8, 2017}}</ref> On April 1, 2018, he hit 4 million subscribers. On April 15, 2018, Douglass won the 2018 [[Shorty Awards|Shorty Award]] for YouTuber of the Year, which he accepted while dressed in a [[Garfield]] costume.<ref name=Shorty2018>{{cite web|url=http://shortyawards.com/category/10th/youtuber|title=YouTuber of the Year|publisher=[[Shorty Awards]]|accessdate=April 16, 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180416064848/http://shortyawards.com/category/10th/youtuber|archivedate=April 16, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==== ''JackAsk'' and ''Yesterday I Asked You'' (2014\u2013present) ====\n<!-- linked from redirects [[YIAY]] and [[Yiay]] -->\nOn January 8, 2014, Douglass launched a new series entitled ''JackAsk'', in which he answers viewers' questions in a satirical way. The intro and logo for the series are a reference to the TV series of a similar name, [[Jackass (TV series)|Jackass]]. {{As of|2020|03|df=}}, there are 100 episodes.\n\nOn February 3, 2015, Douglass started a daily series on his secondary channel jackisanerd, titled ''Yesterday I Asked You'' (''YIAY''), in which he asks his viewers a question and reads his favorite answers to the viewers. After 15 days of uploading ''YIAY'' videos to his second channel, jackisanerd, he moved the series to his main channel, jacksfilms, and has released episodes on it since. As of March 2020, he has uploaded 499 episodes making it the biggest series on his channel. He also briefly operated a live version of this series known as ''YIAY LIVE'' in which he had live viewers compete for the best answer to a given question.\n\nOn November 20, 2015, Douglass started a new series on the [[Regal Cinemas]] YouTube channel named ''Jack Talks Trailers'', in which he gives a brief recap of new film trailers that are released within the past week. At the end of each episode, Douglass reads the opinions of people's thoughts about a specific trailer shown in the episode. Douglass' last video for Regal was uploaded July 29, 2016.<ref>{{Citation|last=Regal Cinemas|title=Jack Talks Trailers: Episode 1: Finding Dory & Warcraft - Regal Cinemas [HD]|date=November 20, 2015|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cdpR40Hh63o|accessdate=May 13, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=jacksfilms|title=NEW SERIES!|date=November 21, 2015|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JIbZFjYTCbE|accessdate=May 13, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn March 21, 2016, Douglass uploaded an [[iPhone SE (1st generation)|first-generation iPhone SE]] parody in which he mocks the phone for the small screen size.<ref>{{cite web|title=iPhone SE parody commercial says what everyone's thinking|url=https://www.cnet.com/au/news/iphone-se-parody-commercial-says-what-everyones-thinking/|website=CNET|accessdate=17 September 2017|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Douglass|first1=Jack|title=iPhone SE (parody)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Bfktt22nUG4|website=YouTube|date=21 March 2016}}</ref> In March 2017, Douglass uploaded a video titled ''[[Samsung Galaxy S8|Galaxy S8]] first look (parody)'' which has earned more than a million views.<ref name=\"cnetS8\">{{cite web|title=Samsung Galaxy S8 video trending on YouTube isn't flattering|url=https://www.cnet.com/au/news/samsung-galaxy-s8-video-trending-on-youtube-isnt-flattering/|website=CNET|accessdate=17 September 2017|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Douglass|first1=Jack|title=Galaxy S8 first look (parody)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2WMEPWEavRY|website=YouTube|accessdate=17 September 2017|date=29 March 2017}}</ref> In September, Douglass made an [[iPhone X]] parody which has over 3 million views (making joking claims including, \"The [[Face ID]] shoot[s] thousands of lasers straight into your pores. Then it sucks out your soul, much like a [[Dementor]]\").<ref>{{cite web|title=It's What Steve Jobs Would've Wanted|url=https://www.kotaku.com.au/2017/09/its-what-steve-jobs-wouldve-wanted/|website=Kotaku Australia|accessdate=17 September 2017|language=en|date=14 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Douglass|first1=Jack|title=iPhone X (parody)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sjlHnJvXdQs|website=YouTube|accessdate=17 September 2017|date=12 September 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"cnetX\">{{cite web|title=Apple iPhone X parody video snarks at '$1,000 emoji machine'|url=https://www.cnet.com/au/news/apple-iphone-x-parody-jacksfilms-emoji-machine-video/|website=CNET|accessdate=17 September 2017|language=en}}</ref> Douglass also made several references to ''[[Game of Thrones]]'' in the videos.<ref name=\"cnetS8\" /><ref name=\"cnetX\" />\n\nDouglass appeared in [[YouTube Rewind#.22YouTube Rewind: The Ultimate 2016 Challenge.22|YouTube Rewind 2016]] and [[YouTube Rewind#.22YouTube Rewind: The Ultimate 2016 Challenge.22|YouTube Rewind 2017]].<ref name=\"rewind\">{{cite web|last1=Douglass|first1=Jake|title=TOO HOT for YOUTUBE REWIND? (JackAsk #74)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=e7KLLikFHys|website=YouTube|accessdate=17 September 2017|date=14 December 2016}}</ref> He also attended [[E3 2017]], where he filmed a sketch video; and [[E3 2018]], where he filmed an episode of YIAY.\n\nOn January 30, 2017, Douglass referred to ''[[The Emoji Movie]]'' for the first time in his video ''How do we fix YouTube? (YIAY #309)''.<ref>{{cite web|author1=jacksfilms|title=How do we fix YouTube? (YIAY #309)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5vTYaAU0nrw|website=YouTube|accessdate=1 August 2017|date=30 January 2017}}</ref> Douglass referenced ''The Emoji Movie'' frequently in 2017, making a parody of the trailer and selling merchandise of the date of its release, July 28. His videos, \"''Frame-by-frame analysis of The Emoji Movie Trailer''\", \"''THE EMOJI MOVIE - Trailer #2''\", and \"''Counting down to The Emoji Movie while spinning 15 [[fidget spinner]]s and [[Dab (dance)|dabbing]] every 60 seconds''\" have over 5 million views combined, {{as of|2017|11|lc=y}}.<ref>{{cite web|title=THE EMOJI MOVIE - Trailer #2|url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=e1C6bm52f5Q|publisher=YouTube|work=jacksfilms|date=April 27, 2017|accessdate = July 15, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=JULY 28 - UNISEX T-SHIRT|url=https://shop.crowdmade.com/collections/jacksfilms/products/emoji-movie-2-unisex-t-shirt|publisher=Crowdmade|work=jacksfilms|date=April 27, 2017|accessdate=July 15, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170728200743/https://shop.crowdmade.com/collections/jacksfilms/products/emoji-movie-2-unisex-t-shirt|archive-date=July 28, 2017|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On July 20, Douglass received a package from the marketing team at [[Sony Pictures Animation]], thanking him for being \"the [No. 1] fan of ''The Emoji Movie''\", inviting him to the world premiere on July 23, and sending ''Emoji Movie''-related merchandise, including fidget spinners, face masks of ''Emoji Movie'' characters, and a [[Stuffed toy|plushie]] of Poop.<ref>{{cite web |last=Dryden |first=Liam |url=http://www.wetheunicorns.com/news/jacksfilms-emoji-movie-premiere/ |title=JacksFilms Got The Best Response After Trolling The Sh*t Out Of 'The Emoji Movie' |date=July 21, 2017 |work=We the Unicorns |accessdate=July 22, 2017}}</ref> The video in which Douglass unboxed the package and discussed his invitation has received over 2 million views.<ref>{{cite web|title=I got invited to the world premiere of The Emoji Movie|url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=D1-Lnk99G1U|publisher=YouTube|work=jacksfilms|date=July 21, 2017|accessdate = July 15, 2017}}</ref> On July 28, Douglass uploaded a review of the film, hinting at the large amounts of product placement but generally acting as if he enjoyed the film. The review has received over 6 million views.<ref>{{cite web|author1=jacksfilms|title=THE EMOJI MOVIE REVIEW|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UWn8zsYtbtY|website=YouTube|accessdate=28 July 2017|date=28 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2019, Douglass posted a video where he asked people on the street, \"Can ANYONE name a single character from the movie ''[[Avatar (2009 film)|Avatar]]''?\". Only one respondent was able to name a character from the film.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Neilan |first1=Dan |title=Nobody can name a single character in Avatar, apparently |url=https://news.avclub.com/nobody-can-name-a-single-character-in-avatar-apparentl-1833493985 |website=The A.V. Club |accessdate=March 26, 2019 |date=March 22, 2019}}</ref> In May, Douglass posted a video titled \"Watch Endgame. Beat Avatar.\", in which he urged the viewers to watch ''[[Avengers: Endgame]]'' and make the film take ''Avatar's'' title as \"[[List of highest-grossing films|The top-grossing film of all time]]\".<ref>{{cite web|author1=jacksfilms|title=Watch Endgame. Beat Avatar.|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Eb9Z8gutG8I|website=YouTube|date=May 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Collaborations and other appearances ===\n<!-- linked from redirect [[The Sideburns Crew]] -->\n[[File:TobyTurnerJackDouglassVidCon2012.jpg|thumb|Douglass performing with [[Toby Turner]] at [[VidCon 2012]]]]\nDouglass' relocation to [[Los Angeles]] from [[Maryland]] offered opportunities to collaborate with fellow YouTube users and expand his audience. The success of his collaborations with [[Toby Turner]] and [[Sean Klitzner]] led to the trio being nicknamed \"The Sideburns Crew\".<ref name=\"YGS100video\">{{cite AV media|url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AEmPk7uAQ34|title=YGS #100|publisher=[[YouTube]]|work=jacksfilms|date=November 20, 2015|accessdate = December 10, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Douglass|first1=Jack|title=THE VALENTINES DAY SONG|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DXtXHkgalwM|website=YouTube|accessdate=17 September 2017|date=14 February 2012}}</ref> Douglass also filmed videos for Los Angeles-based YouTube partner Olga Karavaeva, more commonly referred to as [[Olga Kay]]. He has also collaborated with [[Shane Dawson]], Vincent Cyr, [[Onision]] and Stefan Li among others. Douglass has also featured as a voice guest in the asdfmovie series and other sketches by [[TomSka]]. On September 26, 2011, Douglass uploaded \"Take Off Your Clothes (Like [[Scarlett Johansson]])\".<ref>{{cite web|author=Joe Miragliotta|url=http://www.joesdaily.com/2011/09/26/take-off-your-clothes-like-scarlett-johansson/|title=TAKE OFF YOUR CLOTHES (LIKE SCARLETT JOHANSSON)|publisher=Joe's Daily|date=September 26, 2011|accessdate=June 29, 2012}}</ref> On July 23, 2012, he uploaded \"The Ray William Johnson Song\", which featured ten other YouTube stars including Olga Kay, [[PewDiePie|Felix Kjellberg]] and [[Steve Kardynal]]. On September 23, 2012, he uploaded \"''Your Grammar Sucks #40''\", which featured YouTube performers including the [[Fine Brothers]] and Brock Baker. Douglass has appeared on the [[h3h3Productions|H3 Podcast]] numerous times, typically accompanied by fellow YouTube creator Erik Hoffstad. A September 2017 episode featuring Douglass gained notable controversy after host Ethan Klein's criticism of [[PewDiePie]]'s use of the [[Nigger|\"N-word\"]] during a livestream, receiving over 30 thousand dislikes.<ref>{{Citation|url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=W555pdLeI_I|accessdate = February 22, 2019|title = H3 Podcast #17}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ey7zaPv00fo|accessdate = February 22, 2019|title = H3 Podcast #29}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3wV4TxJ8dA8|accessdate = February 22, 2019|title = H3 Podcast #46}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OcQl2ra57ME|accessdate = February 22, 2019|title = H3 Podcast #64}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0oLt5qfxtxQ|accessdate = February 22, 2019|title = H3 Podcast #98}}</ref>\n\nDouglass is also known for playing the role of [[List of MyMusic characters#Intern 2/Flowchart|Intern 2]] on ''[[MyMusic]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://whatstrending.com/2013/09/jack-douglass-adam-busch-mymusic-season-2-making-youtube-magic-fine-bros/|title=Jack Douglass And Adam Busch On \"MyMusic\" Season 2 And Making YouTube Magic with the Fine Bros|author=Amanda Walgrove|first=|date=September 6, 2013|website=|publisher=What's Trending?|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131004221240/http://whatstrending.com/2013/09/jack-douglass-adam-busch-mymusic-season-2-making-youtube-magic-fine-bros/|archivedate=October 4, 2013|accessdate=October 1, 2013}}</ref> a defunct show funded by YouTube's $100&nbsp;million [[YouTube Original Channel Initiative|original channel initiative]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.techi.com/2011/10/youtube-expands-its-exclusive-content-drive-with-100-new-video-channels/|title=YouTube expands its exclusive-content drive with 100 new video channels|author=Connor Livingston|first=|date=October 29, 2011|website=|publisher=Techi|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160322122712/http://www.techi.com/2011/10/youtube-expands-its-exclusive-content-drive-with-100-new-video-channels/|archive-date=March 22, 2016|accessdate=June 9, 2013}}</ref> ''[[MyMusic]]'' has over 430,000 subscribers and over 48.2&nbsp;million video views as of September 4, 2018.\n\nIn 2014, Douglass began voicing Jimmy, the protagonist in ''16-Bit High'', an animated series launched by [[Smosh Games]].<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Jarvey|first=Natalie|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/sxsw-smosh-games-launches-two-686776|title=SXSW Exclusive: Smosh Games Launches Two New YouTube Series (Video)|magazine=Hollywood Reporter|date=March 7, 2014|accessdate=April 7, 2014}}</ref> In October 2015, Douglass portrayed \"Pippen\" in the film ''[[Bob Thunder: Internet Assassin]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSnCCN4LPs3B+1d9+MKW20150925 |title=Influencer Comedy Film \"Bob Thunder: Internet Assassin\" Trailer Debuts |work=Reuters |date=September 25, 2015 |accessdate=April 16, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160426005555/https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSnCCN4LPs3B%2B1d9%2BMKW20150925 |archive-date=April 26, 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\n<!-- linked from redirect [[Kristen Klessig]] -->\n\nOn January 1, 2017, Douglass became engaged to his longtime partner Erin Elizabeth Breslin.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.j-14.com/posts/youtube-jack-douglass-engaged-erin-elizabeth-breslin-122557/photos/kelsea1-221818 |title=YouTube Star Jack Douglass Is Engaged to Longtime Girlfriend Erin Elizabeth Breslin |last=Rodriguez |first=Karla |website=[[J-14 (magazine)|J-14]] |publication-date=January 6, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Jacksfilms on Twitter|url=https://twitter.com/jacksfilms/status/816127315449118721|website=Twitter|accessdate=2 August 2017}}</ref> The couple married on April 21, 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BecHPxqHOHZ/|title=Instagram post by E.E. \ud83c\udf40 \u2022 Jan 27, 2018 at 4:20am UTC|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=2018-02-05}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=jacksfilms|title=Wedding Hashtags (YIAY #330)|date=2017-05-22|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3J43TouOsqM|accessdate=2017-12-08}}</ref> Douglass owns two [[American Eskimo Dog|American Eskimo]] dogs named Klondike and Sundae. Their dog, Klondike inspired Douglass to create a new line of merchandise named after her. A semi-satirical dig at [[Logan Paul]]'s \"Be a Maverick\" clothing line, the line features images of the Eskimo dog.\n\n== Awards ==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Nominated\n! Award\n! Result\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | {{abbr|Ref(s)|References}}\n|-\n| 2018\n| [[Shorty Awards]]\n| YouTuber of the Year\n| {{won}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |<ref name=Shorty2018/>\n|-\n| 2018\n| [[Streamy Awards]]\n| Overall Comedy\n| {{nominated}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.streamys.org/nominees-winners/8th-annual-nominees/|title=8th Annual Nominees|work=The Streamy Awards|access-date=2018-10-24|language=en-US}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCPcFg7aBbaVzXoIKSNqwaww jacksfilms YouTube channel]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/user/jackisanerd jackisanerd YouTube channel]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120717131845/http://www.vokle.com/series/24487-get-jackd Jack Douglass' ''GET JACK'D'' live chat series] on [[Vokle]] \n* [https://itunes.apple.com/us/artist/jack-douglass/id115996508 Douglass' music] on [[iTunes]]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Douglass, Jack}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American comedians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:American male comedians]]\n[[Category:American male musicians]]\n[[Category:American male voice actors]]\n[[Category:American male web series actors]]\n[[Category:American people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:American University alumni]]\n[[Category:American YouTubers]]\n[[Category:Atholton High School alumni]]\n[[Category:Comedy YouTubers]]\n[[Category:Fullscreen (company) people]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male YouTubers]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Maryland]]\n[[Category:People from Columbia, Maryland]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from Maryland]]\n[[Category:Infomercial parodies]]\n[[Category:Music YouTubers]]\n", "name_user": "Infogapp1", "label": "safe", "comment": "Space and formatting for easier readability", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jack_Douglass"}
{"title_page": "Ideal money", "text_new": "{{non-free|date=December 2017}}\n{{Overquotation|date=April 2015}}\n[[File:John Forbes Nash, Jr..jpg|thumb|410x410px|John Forbes Nash, Jr.]]\n'''Ideal Money''' (to be considered different than defining 'ideal money' without capitals) is a theoretical notion promulgated by [[John Forbes Nash, Jr.|John Nash]] (Nobel Laureate in Economics) to stabilize international currencies. It is a solution to the [[Triffin dilemma]]-the conflict of economic interests between the short-term domestic and long-term international objectives when a currency used in a country is also serving as world reserve currency.\n\nNash gave various lectures and written discourses on the subject he called Ideal Money.<ref>http://www.mediatheque.lindau-nobel.org/videos/31344/ideal-money-and-the-motivation-of-savings-and-thrift-2011</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Je22xKQekCk|title=Ideal Money Lecture|last=Nash|first=John}}</ref> The first talk was given in 1995 (one year after Nash won the [[Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic Sciences|Nobel Prize for economics]] for his work on equilibrium theory nearly 50 years prior).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZO7aDojl6f0|title=Ideal Money lecture 1995|last=Nash|first=John}}</ref> Nash spent 20 years giving talks, in many different nations around the world, about how Ideal Money could be brought about internationally.\n\nNash said in an interview the basic idea for Ideal Money came to him in the late 1950s and early 1960s at a time when he fled the US to Europe in order to try to renounce his US citizenship and exchange his USD for the Swiss Franc (which he believed to be superior in quality from a perspective he describes in Ideal Money).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7Zb6_PZxxA0|title=Food For Thought With John Nash}}</ref>\n\n==Definition==\nNash defines his concept of Ideal Money as: <blockquote>\n....money intrinsically not subject to inflation...<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fermatslibrary.com/|title=Fermat's Library {{!}} Ideal Money Version 2 annotated/explained version.|website=Fermat's Library|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n== ICPI-Industrial Consumption Price Index ==\nIn pursuit of a possible apolitical basis for stable value Nash created a concept he calls an ICPI.  The ICPI is effectively a basket of optimally chosen commodity prices: <blockquote>The ultimately launched concept of \"Ideal Money\" became possible when I conceived of a practical basis for a standardization of the comparison of the value of the currency with an appropriate standard or ideal. And the key to that was the idea of an ICPI or (international) \"Industrial Consumption Price Index\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://fermatslibrary.com/p/213f2919|title=Asymptotically Ideal Money|last=Nash|first=John}}</ref></blockquote><blockquote>This statistic could be calculated from the international prices of commodities such as copper, silver, tungsten, and so forth that are used in industrial activities.</blockquote>\n\n== Asymptotically ideal money ==\nIn an interview with Greek ex-finance minister [[Yanis Varoufakis]] Nash explained that the role of money has changed and evolves: <blockquote>...money plays constantly evolving role, despite the continuity from one era to the next. Flux and Continuity. Presently, economists have focused on the theoretical problem of replacing paper money by plastic of electronic money, as well as on the repercussion of such a replacement.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.yanisvaroufakis.eu/2015/06/02/in-conversation-with-john-nash-jnr-on-ideal-money/|title=In conversation with John Nash Jnr on Ideal Money|last=Varoufakis|first=Yanis}}</ref></blockquote> Nash's narration of the evolution of ideal money through the competition of respective national [[Fiat money|fiat]] and centrally banked currencies starts with the introduction of a possible international money of good quality:<blockquote>In the near future there may be a smaller number of major currencies used in the world and these may stand in competitive relations among themselves. There is now the \"euro\" and the inflationary tradition of the Italian lira seems to be past history now. And there COULD be introduced, for example, a similar international currency for the Islamic world, or for South Asia, or for South America, or here or there.</blockquote>\n\n===Nash's death===\nNash died suddenly in a taxi cab accident involving him and his wife.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2015/may/24/john-nash-mathematician-beautiful-mind-dies-taxi-crash|title=John Nash, mathematician portrayed in A Beautiful Mind, dies in taxi crash at 86}}</ref> On the way home from receiving the Abel prize,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.abelprize.no/nyheter/vis.html?tid=63705|title=John F. Nash, Jr. and his wife Alicia killed in car accident}}</ref> Nash and his wife were forced to take a taxi cab from the airport when their limousine never arrived. They were both thrown from the cab when the driver lost control and neither were wearing seat belts as it was reported the seat belts weren't working.\n\nThe Nashes died on the [[New Jersey Turnpike]] which is coincidental with the abstract opening of the first published version of Ideal Money: <blockquote>Money can be recognized as a technological development comparable to the wheel and of similar antiquity.  Among the more recent developments in the technology that facilitates transfer of utility (in the sense of game theory) are systems like those of EZ Pass, by means of which vehicles traversing toll bridges or toll highways can pay, their toll fees without stopping for the attention of human personnel manning the toll booths.<ref>{{cite journal|jstor=1061553|title=Ideal Money-Southern Economic Journal|last=Nash|first=John|date=July 2002|website=}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n== Possible relation to Bitcoin and emerging cryptocurrency economics ==\n\n=== Is Bitcoin Nash's ideal money? ===\nIt has been asked{{by whom|date=June 2018}} if [[bitcoin]] is an implementation of Nash's Ideal Money (or Asymptotically Ideal Money).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.indiabitcoin.com/can-bitcoin-be-john-nashs-ideal-money-newsbtc/|title=Can Bitcoin be John Nash\u2019s Ideal Money?}}</ref> When asked about bitcoin and Ideal Money Nash responded, \"Bitcoin might not be it but...\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NUyCO3FXHS4|title=JOHN NASH BITCOIN HONESTY}}</ref> He went on to explain how once a strong currency is establish another issuer might try to pass off a lesser valuable \"counterfeit\" for being at par with the honest and well established money:<blockquote>It becomes possible, once Caesar is minting gold and decides its very well used and accepted and the empire is working well on the gold coins, another Caesar might come along and say \u2018Well I can put a little of lead inside these gold coins and pass them out at the same value.\u2019 It would be the Aurelius of so and so\u2026.and that sort of thing can happen.</blockquote>\n\nHal Finney, one of the top contenders for being the person behind the pseudonym Satoshi Nakamoto that created bitcoin,{{cn|date=May 2019}} was interested in Nash's story and works as early as 2002 and described Nash as possibly being a proto-extropian.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://extropians.weidai.com/extropians.1Q02/3146.html|title=John Nash, proto-Extropian?|last=Hal|first=Finney}}</ref>\n\n=== Can Bitcoin be ideal (stable) money? ===\n[[George Selgin]], an expert on [[free banking]] theory, expounds on value proposition of bitcoin in regard to the inability to control its supply (ie inflation targeting):<blockquote>It doesn\u2019t follow, however, that either Bitcoins\u2019 purchasing power or the volume of Bitcoin-denominated payments will be stable enough to make Bitcoins anyone\u2019s idea of a sound money. Because it makes no allowances for changes in the real demand for Bitcoins, whatever their source, the strict \u201cprotocol\u201d that regulates the supply of Bitcoins\u2014a protocol that raises Bitcoin \u201cmining\u201d costs in response to changes in mining activity and technology, but without regard to Bitcoins\u2019 purchasing power\u2014would allow fluctuations in the pure transactions demand for Bitcoins to continue to influence their purchasing power. As the number approaches 21 million, mining rewards will approach zero, and Bitcoin output with cease once and for all. The transactions demand for Bitcoins will, in contrast, tend to go on increasing with economic growth. A Bitcoin standard would thus tend to result in a rate of deflation at least equal to the rate of economic growth, with occasional bouts of more severe deflation occurring with every cyclical increase in the demand for money. Although (as I\u2019ve argued elsewhere) deflation needn\u2019t go hand-in-hand with recession or depression so long as the rate of deflation reflects an economy\u2019s (total factor) productivity growth rate, chances are that deflation in a Bitcoin economy would frequently exceed this safe limit.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hillsdale.edu/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/FMF-2014-Bitcoin-Problems-and-Prospects.pdf|title=Bitcoin: Problems and Prospects|last=Selgin|first=George|date=Nov 2014}}</ref></blockquote>Because bitcoin's supply was predetermined at inception<ref>[https://en.bitcoin.it/wiki/Controlled_supply]</ref> and considered unchangeable it cannot fluctuate with the demand cycles and thus Selgin suggests it cannot be made very stable in regard to its purchasing power.  However, this still leaves the possibility that bitcoin fits Nash's concept of \"Asymptotically Ideal Money\". Whether Nash was specifically referring to bitcoin or not it still might have the same effect and lead to the intended result of international stability of the existing legacy fiat currencies (and possibly in relation to bitcoin).\n\nAlthough bitcoin might not be Ideal Money Nash would consider it to be \"good money\" because of its comparability to gold based on its supply restraint and predictability:<blockquote>To be quite respectable, in a Gresham-advised sense, money needs only to be AS GOOD as other material commodities that might be hoarded.</blockquote>This makes it an interesting consideration for the basis of Nash's premise suggesting Ideal Money could be an enthymeme for bitcoin: <blockquote>\u2026intrinsically free of \u201cinflationary decadence\u201d..a true \u201cgold standard\u201d, but the proposed basis for that was not the proposal of a linkage to gold</blockquote>\n\n== Ideal money as fiat ==\nThe implementation of centrally banked digital currencies, such as many nations and central banks are studying and testing,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bankofcanada.ca/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/sdp2017-16.pdf|title=Central Bank Digital Currency: Motivations and Implications}}</ref> might also give rise to a possibility for the implementation of Ideal Money via a digitally secured peg [this is conjecture of the editor] to a basket of digitally based nationally currencies.\n\n== Nashification vs hyperbitcoinization ==\nIt has been shown{{by whom|date=June 2018}} that Nashification, the process of the asymptotic approach to an \"ideal\" of inter-national stability of major currencies is comparable to the end observation of the result of \"hyperbitcoinization\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nakamotoinstitute.org/mempool/hyperbitcoinization/|title=Hyperbitcoinization|last=Krawisz|first=Daniel}}</ref>  That is to say, hyperbitcoinization, which is the implication bitcoin will becomes the single world currency, does satisfy Nash's proposal to have internationally stable money:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/@rextar4444/nashification-vs-bitcoinization-d8ec9b8bce3f|title=Nashification Vs. Bitcoinization}}</ref><blockquote>When all major currencies\u2019 purchasing power changes at the same rate that would signal the advent of Ideal Money (Nashification).</blockquote><blockquote>In regard to hyperbiticoinization as an end in which bitcoin serves as a global currency, this would be a comparable \u201cfor all intents and purposes\u201d end as Nashification.</blockquote>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.fordham.edu/Campus_Resources/eNewsroom/Archives/2008/archive_1377.asp Fordham eNewsroom on Nash's 2008 lecture]\n* [http://www.investopedia.com/terms/n/nash-equilibrium.asp Nash Equilibrium]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ideal Money}}\n[[Category:Monetary economics]]\n", "text_old": "{{non-free|date=December 2017}}\n{{Overquotation|date=April 2015}}\n[[File:John Forbes Nash, Jr..jpg|thumb|410x410px|John Forbes Nash, Jr.]]\n'''Ideal Money''' (to be considered different than defining 'ideal money' without capitals) is a theoretical notion promulgated by [[John Forbes Nash, Jr.|John Nash]] (Nobel Laureate in Economics) to stabilize international currencies. It is a solution to the [[Triffin dilemma]]-the conflict of economic interests between the short-term domestic and long-term international objectives when a currency used in a country is also serving as world reserve currency.\n\nNash gave various lectures and written discourses on the subject he called Ideal Money.<ref>http://www.mediatheque.lindau-nobel.org/videos/31344/ideal-money-and-the-motivation-of-savings-and-thrift-2011</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Je22xKQekCk|title=Ideal Money Lecture|last=Nash|first=John}}</ref> The first talk was given in 1995 (one year after Nash won the [[Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic Sciences|Nobel Prize for economics]] for his work on equilibrium theory nearly 50 years prior).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZO7aDojl6f0|title=Ideal Money lecture 1995|last=Nash|first=John}}</ref> Nash spent 20 years giving talks, in many different nations around the world, about how Ideal Money could be brought about internationally.\n\nNash said in an interview the basic idea for Ideal Money came to him in the late 1950s and early 1960s at a time when he fled the US to Europe in order to try to renounce his US citizenship and exchange his USD for the Swiss Franc (which he believed to be superior in quality from a perspective he describes in Ideal Money).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7Zb6_PZxxA0|title=Food For Thought With John Nash}}</ref>\n\n==Definition==\nNash defines his concept of Ideal Money as: <blockquote>\n....money intrinsically not subject to inflation...<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fermatslibrary.com/|title=Fermat's Library {{!}} Ideal Money Version 2 annotated/explained version.|website=Fermat's Library|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n== ICPI-Industrial Consumption Price Index ==\nIn pursuit of a possible apolitical basis for stable value Nash created a concept he calls an ICPI.  The ICPI is effectively a basket of optimally chosen commodity prices: <blockquote>The ultimately launched concept of \"Ideal Money\" became possible when I conceived of a practical basis for a standardization of the comparison of the value of the currency with an appropriate standard or ideal. And the key to that was the idea of an ICPI or (international) \"Industrial Consumption Price Index\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://fermatslibrary.com/p/213f2919|title=Asymptotically Ideal Money|last=Nash|first=John}}</ref></blockquote><blockquote>This statistic could be calculated from the international prices of commodities such as copper, silver, tungsten, and so forth that are used in industrial activities.</blockquote>\n\n== Asymptotically ideal money ==\nIn an interview with Greek ex-finance minister [[Yanis Varoufakis]] Nash explained that the role of money has changed and evolves: <blockquote>...money plays constantly evolving role, despite the continuity from one era to the next. Flux and Continuity. Presently, economists have focused on the theoretical problem of replacing paper money by