ly]</ref> and considered unchangeable it cannot fluctuate with the demand cycles and thus Selgin suggests it cannot be made very stable in regard to its purchasing power.  However, this still leaves the possibility that bitcoin fits Nash's concept of \"Asymptotically Ideal Money\". Whether Nash was specifically referring to bitcoin or not it still might have the same effect and lead to the intended result of international stability of the existing legacy fiat currencies (and possibly in relation to bitcoin).\n\nAlthough bitcoin might not be Ideal Money Nash would consider it to be \"good money\" because of its comparability to gold based on its supply restraint and predictability:<blockquote>To be quite respectable, in a Gresham-advised sense, money needs only to be AS GOOD as other material commodities that might be hoarded.</blockquote>This makes it an interesting consideration for the basis of Nash's premise suggesting Ideal Money could be an enthymeme for bitcoin: <blockquote>\u2026intrinsically free of \u201cinflationary decadence\u201d..a true \u201cgold standard\u201d, but the proposed basis for that was not the proposal of a linkage to gold</blockquote>\n\n== Ideal money as fiat ==\nThe implementation of centrally banked digital currencies, such as many nations and central banks are studying and testing,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bankofcanada.ca/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/sdp2017-16.pdf|title=Central Bank Digital Currency: Motivations and Implications}}</ref> might also give rise to a possibility for the implementation of Ideal Money via a digitally secured peg to a basket of digitally based nationally currencies.\n\n== Nashification vs hyperbitcoinization ==\nIt has been shown{{by whom|date=June 2018}} that Nashification, the process of the asymptotic approach to an \"ideal\" of inter-national stability of major currencies is comparable to the end observation of the result of \"hyperbitcoinization\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nakamotoinstitute.org/mempool/hyperbitcoinization/|title=Hyperbitcoinization|last=Krawisz|first=Daniel}}</ref>  That is to say, hyperbitcoinization, which is the implication bitcoin will becomes the single world currency, does satisfy Nash's proposal to have internationally stable money:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/@rextar4444/nashification-vs-bitcoinization-d8ec9b8bce3f|title=Nashification Vs. Bitcoinization}}</ref><blockquote>When all major currencies\u2019 purchasing power changes at the same rate that would signal the advent of Ideal Money (Nashification).</blockquote><blockquote>In regard to hyperbiticoinization as an end in which bitcoin serves as a global currency, this would be a comparable \u201cfor all intents and purposes\u201d end as Nashification.</blockquote>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.fordham.edu/Campus_Resources/eNewsroom/Archives/2008/archive_1377.asp Fordham eNewsroom on Nash's 2008 lecture]\n* [http://www.investopedia.com/terms/n/nash-equilibrium.asp Nash Equilibrium]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ideal Money}}\n[[Category:Monetary economics]]\n", "name_user": "2.24.15.147", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ideal_money"}
{"title_page": "Found Out About You", "text_new": "{{short description|1989 song by Gin Blossoms}}\n{{for|a song by Emily Osment|All the Right Wrongs}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name     = Found Out About You\n| cover    =\n| alt      =\n| type     = Song\n| artist   = [[Gin Blossoms]]\n| album    = [[Dusted (Gin Blossoms album)|Dusted]]\n| released = May 13, 1989 {{small|(album)}}\n| format   =\n| recorded = Whipping Post Studios in [[Tucson, Arizona]] in May, 1989\n| studio   =\n| venue    =\n| genre    = [[Alternative rock]], [[jangle pop]]\n| length   =\n| label    = San Jacinto\n| writer   = [[Doug Hopkins]]\n| producer = Rich Hopkins\n}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Found Out About You\n| cover      = Gin Blossoms Found Out About You.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Gin Blossoms]]\n| album      = [[New Miserable Experience]]\n| released   = 1993\n| format     = [[CD single]], [[Cassette single|cassette]]\n| recorded   = 1992\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Alternative rock]], [[jangle pop]]\n| length     = 3:53\n| label      = [[Fontana Records|Fontana]], [[A&M Records|A&M]]\n| writer     = [[Doug Hopkins]]\n| producer   =\n| prev_title = [[Until I Fall Away]]\n| prev_year  = 1994\n| next_title = [[Allison Road]]\n| next_year  = 1994\n}}\n\n\"'''Found Out About You'''\" is the fourth single from the [[Gin Blossoms]]' second album ''[[New Miserable Experience]]'', recorded in 1992.   Written by lead guitarist [[Doug Hopkins]], who was fired from the band after the album, the Gin Blossoms had previously recorded it on their 1989 debut album ''[[Dusted (Gin Blossoms album)|Dusted]]''.\n\n\"Found Out About You\" reached number 25 on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], making it the second single from the album (after \"[[Hey Jealousy]]\") to enter the top 40. The song found the most success in Canada, where it reached number three on the ''[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]'' Top Singles chart. Elsewhere, the song barely reached the top 40 in the United Kingdom and peaked at number 94 on Australia's [[ARIA Singles Chart]] in September 1994.\n\n==Charts==\n===Weekly charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n!scope=\"col\"|Chart (1994)\n!scope=\"col\"|Peak<br>position\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Australia ([[ARIA Charts|ARIA]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://i.imgur.com/IcGFZti.jpg|title=The ARIA Australian Top 100 Singles Chart \u2013 Week Ending 02 October 1994|publisher=[[Australian Recording Industry Association|ARIA]]|accessdate=February 29, 2016}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|94\n|-\n{{singlechart|Canadatopsingles|3|chartid=2382|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 15, 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Scotland|51|date=19940409|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 15, 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|UK|40|date=19940416|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 15, 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardhot100|25|artist=Gin Blossoms|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 15, 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardadultcontemporary|31|artist=Gin Blossoms|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 15, 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardadultpopsongs|38|artist=Gin Blossoms|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 15, 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardalternativesongs|1|artist=Gin Blossoms|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 15, 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardmainstreamrock|5|artist=Gin Blossoms|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 15, 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardpopsongs|6|artist=Gin Blossoms|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 15, 2018}}\n|}\n\n{{listen\n | filename    = Gin Blossoms - Found Out About You.ogg\n | title       = \"Found Out About You\" (1994)\n | description = \n | format      = [[Ogg]]\n}}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n!scope=\"col\"|Chart (1994)\n!scope=\"col\"|Position\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Canada Top Singles (''RPM'')<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/rpm/Pages/image.aspx?Image=nlc008388.2687&URLjpg=http%3a%2f%2fwww.collectionscanada.gc.ca%2fobj%2f028020%2ff4%2fnlc008388.2687.gif&Ecopy=nlc008388.2687|title=RPM Top 100 Hit Tracks of 1994|work=[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]|publisher=[[Library and Archives Canada]]|accessdate=December 1, 2018}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|35\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|US ''Billboard'' Hot 100<ref>{{cite web|url=http://longboredsurfer.com/charts.php?year=1994 |title=Billboard Top 100 - 1994 |accessdate=2010-08-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090301121519/http://longboredsurfer.com/charts.php?year=1994 |archivedate=2009-03-01 }}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|51\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Number one modern rock hits of 1994]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|gin-blossoms|found-out-about-you}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Gin Blossoms}}\n\n[[Category:1993 singles]]\n[[Category:Gin Blossoms songs]]\n[[Category:Billboard Alternative Songs number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Doug Hopkins]]\n[[Category:1989 songs]]\n[[Category:Fontana Records singles]]\n[[Category:A&M Records singles]]\n\n\n{{1990s-rock-song-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1989 song by Gin Blossoms}}\n{{for|a song by Emily Osment|All the Right Wrongs}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name     = Found Out About You\n| cover    =\n| alt      =\n| type     = Song\n| artist   = [[Gin Blossoms]]\n| album    = [[Dusted (Gin Blossoms album)|Dusted]]\n| released = May 13, 1989 {{small|(album)}}\n| format   =\n| recorded = Whipping Post Studios in [[Tucson, Arizona]] in May, 1989\n| studio   =\n| venue    =\n| genre    = [[Alternative rock]], [[jangle pop]]\n| length   =\n| label    = San Jacinto\n| writer   = [[Doug Hopkins]]\n| producer = Rich Hopkins\n}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Found Out About You\n| cover      = Gin Blossoms Found Out About You.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Gin Blossoms]]\n| album      = [[New Miserable Experience]]\n| released   = 1993\n| format     = [[CD single]], [[Cassette single|cassette]]\n| recorded   = 1992\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Alternative rock]], [[jangle pop]]\n| length     = 3:53\n| label      = [[Fontana Records|Fontana]], [[A&M Records|A&M]]\n| writer     = [[Doug Hopkins]]\n| producer   =\n| prev_title = [[Until I Fall Away]]\n| prev_year  = 1994\n| next_title = [[Allison Road]]\n| next_year  = 1994\n}}\n\n\"'''Found Out About You'''\" is the fourth single from the [[Gin Blossoms]]' second album ''[[New Miserable Experience]]'', recorded in 1992.   Written by lead guitarist [[Doug Hopkins]], who was fired from the band after the album, the Gin Blossoms had previously recorded it on their 1989 debut album ''[[Dusted (Gin Blossoms album)|Dusted]]''.\n\n\"Found Out About You\" reached number 25 on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], making it the second single from the album (after \"[[Hey Jealousy]]\") to enter the top 40. The song found the most success in Canada, where it reached number three on the ''[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]''  Top Singles chart. Elsewhere, the song barely reached the top 40 in the United Kingdom and peaked at number 94 on Australia's [[ARIA Singles Chart]] in September 1994.\n\n==Charts==\n===Weekly charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n!scope=\"col\"|Chart (1994)\n!scope=\"col\"|Peak<br>position\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Australia ([[ARIA Charts|ARIA]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://i.imgur.com/IcGFZti.jpg|title=The ARIA Australian Top 100 Singles Chart \u2013 Week Ending 02 October 1994|publisher=[[Australian Recording Industry Association|ARIA]]|accessdate=February 29, 2016}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|94\n|-\n{{singlechart|Canadatopsingles|3|chartid=2382|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 15, 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Scotland|51|date=19940409|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 15, 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|UK|40|date=19940416|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 15, 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardhot100|25|artist=Gin Blossoms|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 15, 2018}}\n|-\n{{s